[One wonders if the patient had traveled previously to any areas that are
known to be endemic for dengue. If so, this could have been his second
infection with dengue, and this time to a different one of the 4 dengue
virus serotypes from his primary infection. The 4 antigenically related
dengue virus serotypes (DEN1-4), are each capable of causing clinical
dengue fever. There is evidence that dengue hemorrhagic fever/dengue shock
syndrome may occur when a dengue virus of a different serotype from the one
which caused the primary infection infects an individual who has antibodies
to the serotype of the primary infection. Infection with a particular
dengue virus serotype does not confer immunity to the other serotypes but
may, instead, result in severe disease manifesting as DHF/DSS.
For those readers interested in further discussion on theories of the
pathogenesis of DHF/DSS and on the history of DHF/DSS, the three postings
cited above from 1999 are worth reading. - Man. Ed. DS
